, Henry James and Edith Wharton articulated their political thought in response to the liberalism that reigned in Boston and, more specifically, at Harvard University, this book shows how each of these authors interrogated that liberalism's arguments for education, democracy and the political duties of the cultivated elite. Coit shows that the works of these authors contributed to a realist critique of a liberal New England idealism that fed into the narrative about 'the genteel tradition', which shaped the study of US literature during the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and cricitism. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiberalismzMassachusettszBostonxHistoryy19th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aBoggs, Colleen Glenney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFumagalli, Maria Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311078040640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147447542640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474475426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474475426/original  a978-3-11-078040-6  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK